We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict mean_trust_value with propensity_value, complacency_value, reliability and exposure (formula: mean_trust_value ~ propensity_value + complacency_value + reliability * exposure + exposure + reliability). The model included reliability and ID as random effects (formula: ~reliability | ID). The model's total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.84) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.31. The model's intercept, corresponding to propensity_value = 0, complacency_value = 0, reliability = high and exposure = 1, is at 4.89 (95% CI [1.70, 8.09], t(179) = 3.00, p = 0.003). Within this model:

  - The effect of propensity_value is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.17, 95% CI [-0.48, 0.83], t(179) = 0.52, p = 0.604; Std. beta = 0.09, 95% CI [-0.26, 0.45])
  - The effect of complacency_value is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.07, 95% CI [-1.26, 1.12], t(179) = -0.12, p = 0.905; Std. beta = -0.02, 95% CI [-0.39, 0.35])
  - The effect of reliability [low] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -1.17, 95% CI [-1.61, -0.73], t(179) = -5.20, p < .001; Std. beta = -0.86, 95% CI [-1.18, -0.53])
  - The effect of exposure [2] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.29, 95% CI [0.07, 0.51], t(179) = 2.63, p = 0.008; Std. beta = 0.21, 95% CI [0.05, 0.37])
  - The interaction effect of exposure [2] on reliability [low] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -0.92, 95% CI [-1.29, -0.55], t(179) = -4.88, p < .001; Std. beta = -0.67, 95% CI [-0.94, -0.40])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using the Wald approximation.

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict mean_trust_value with reliability and exposure (formula: mean_trust_value ~ reliability * exposure). The model included reliability and ID as random effects (formula: ~reliability | ID). The model's total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.84) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.29. The model's intercept, corresponding to reliability = high and exposure = 1, is at 5.52 (95% CI [5.16, 5.89], t(207) = 29.66, p < .001). Within this model:

  - The effect of reliability [low] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -1.10, 95% CI [-1.51, -0.69], t(207) = -5.24, p < .001; Std. beta = -0.84, 95% CI [-1.16, -0.53])
  - The effect of exposure [2] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.24, 95% CI [0.05, 0.44], t(207) = 2.43, p = 0.015; Std. beta = 0.19, 95% CI [0.04, 0.34])
  - The interaction effect of exposure [2] on reliability [low] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -0.80, 95% CI [-1.14, -0.47], t(207) = -4.70, p < .001; Std. beta = -0.62, 95% CI [-0.87, -0.36])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using the Wald approximation.
